WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:03.760
So I’ve lived in the UK all my life and&nbsp;
I’ve always asked myself the question&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:05.520
“Why is it always so rainy?”

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:08.800
Now in my head, this was sort&nbsp;
of a rhetorical question.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:12.160
It’s rainy because it’s&nbsp;
the UK and the UK is rainy.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:14.800
But is the UK actually that rainy?

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:21.440
Firstly, yes... Yes, it is. But secondly when&nbsp;
I looked into it, according to the World Bank&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:27.360
there are 73 other countries that have higher&nbsp;
Average precipitation in mm depth per year. Some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:34.240
of these countries include Bangladesh, Jamaica,&nbsp;
New Zealand, Japan, Switzerland, Norway, and Peru.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:40.000
These statistics however don’t actually take into&nbsp;
account how often it rains, however. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.160
if it rains heavily in one country for&nbsp;
a week out of the year and only rains&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:48.400
lightly in another for 16 weeks out&nbsp;
of the year it’s possible that the one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:52.160
with heavy rains might have a higher&nbsp;
Average precipitation depth in mm.

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:56.800
But why does it rain so much in the UK?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.440 --> 00:01:00.880
It turns out this is because of&nbsp;
something known as the Gulf Stream.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:06.160
The Gulf Stream is a warm and swift Atlantic Ocean&nbsp;
current that originates in the Gulf of Mexico and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:10.560
stretches to the tip of Florida and follows&nbsp;
the eastern coastlines of the United States.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:14.640
This warm current carries on through the Atlantic&nbsp;
until it reaches the west coast of Europe.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:17.920
In the summer this is a pretty good thing&nbsp;
actually because it brings with it some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:22.320
warmer weather. In the winter, however… Warm&nbsp;
water evaporates faster than cool water and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:27.200
considering that the UK is surrounded by seas&nbsp;
it becomes evident why there is so much rain.

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:30.720
So next time it’s raining and you’ve&nbsp;
forgotten your umbrella. You can thank&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:35.120
the Mexican gulf for getting you all&nbsp;
cold and wet. Well actually no it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:39.840
completely our fault that we’re cold but&nbsp;
you can definitely blame it for being wet.

